    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. You mentioned blockages being a hazard. What are the most common things that actually cause a pitot tube to get blocked up or malfunction during flight?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The most common culprits for a blocked pitot tube are often things you'd expect, but they can be surprisingly sneaky, like a small, persistent piece of debris that gets lodged in the opening. Ice accumulation is a major hazard, especially in colder conditions, where freezing moisture builds up inside the tube, effectively sealing it off. You can also encounter foreign object damage (FOD) from insects, dust, or even small bits of bird droppings, which can act like a tiny, persistent dam, preventing the proper flow of air pressure.\n\nIt's a constant battle against the elements and small nuisances, which is why maintenance checks are so important. If you don't check it, you might find it's clogged with something as mundane as a speck of dirt, which is just as dangerous as a large, aggressive chunk of debris. These issues are always a reminder that even the smallest part of the system can have massive consequences in flight safety.",
      "source": "target",
